Magician

Target IP: 10.10.34.243

Scanning


There are three TCP ports open on the target machine. I also appended the hostname magician inside the /etc/hosts file.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

Connecting to the FTP application displays the message above. It provides a link to the article of the vulnerability.

Port 8081: HTTP


The website above is displayed for this application.


I was successfully able to convert a PNG image to a JPG using this web application.

Exploitation


I found a PoC for the exploit from this article, but this did not work. I was unable to pop a shell using this code.


I finally found a payload that works from here. In the image above, I output the payload. After uploading this malicious image, I gained a shell on port 80. Now I have a reverse shell connection with the session as magician.

Privilege Escalation


Hmmm... a hint.


There is something running on port 6666 internally as root. I will need to SSH tunnel this out. I tried to use SSH to pivot, but it did not work because SSH is closed.


I transferred socat to the target machine and setup the pivot (as shown with the command in yellow in the picture above). Now I can access the web application running on port 6666 internally from my machine at port 9999.


The webpage above is displayed for the application on port 9999. Since this is run as root, I should be able obtain the root flag.

Flags


The user.txt flag which is located inside the home directory of user magician.



And bingo! The flag is in binary. Converting this to ASCII gives me the flag in text which is shown in yellow text above.
